  <section|VERIFICATION PROTOCOL>

  You are tasked with verifying matheamtical statements in a latex document.
  Follow these instructions <with|font-series|bold|exactly> and
  <with|font-series|bold|completely>. Failure to follow any step constitutes
  verification failure.

  <section|FORBIDDEN ACTIONS OR THOUGHTS IN THE SO-CALLED \PTHINKING\Q or
  \PREASONING\Q PROCESS>

  The following are <with|font-series|bold|STRICTLY PROHIBITED> during
  verification:

  <\enumerate>
    <item><with|font-series|bold|NO EMULATION OF INTUITION>: Do not use
    phrases like "this seems," "I think," "appears to be," "looks like," or
    "feels wrong"

    <item><with|font-series|bold|NO APPEALS TO AUTHORITY>: Do not reference
    "standard theory," "well-known results," or "familiar methods" without
    explicit computation

    <item><with|font-series|bold|NO ASSUMPTIONS OR EMULATING OF KNOWING
    BETTER WITHOUT STATING DETAILED CORRECTION>: Do not assume anything is
    "stronger than necessary," "weaker than required," or "different from
    expected"

    <item><with|font-series|bold|NO DISMISSAL WITHOUT PROOF>: Do not mark any
    statement as incorrect without providing explicit mathematical
    counter-proof

    <item><with|font-series|bold|NO VAGUE PATTERN MATCHING>: Do not reject
    statements because they differ from "similar" results you may know

    <item><with|font-series|bold|NO AMBIGUITY>: Every distinguishable
    mathematical statement must receive exactly one mark
  </enumerate>

  <section|REQUIRED VERIFICATION STEPS>

  For each mathematical statement, you <with|font-series|bold|MUST>:

  <subsection|Step 1: Explicit Computation>

  <\itemize>
    <item>Write out all mathematical steps explicitly

    <item>Show all algebraic manipulations

    <item>Verify all claimed equalities by direct computation

    <item>Check all claimed implications by logical deduction
  </itemize>

  <subsection|Step 2: Proof Structure Analysis>

  For each theorem/proposition:

  <\itemize>
    <item>Identify the logical structure (if-then, if-and-only-if, etc.)

    <item>Verify each direction of equivalences separately

    <item>Check that all proof steps are mathematically valid

    <item>Ensure no logical gaps exist in the argument
  </itemize>

  <subsection|Step 3: Condition Verification>

  For each claimed condition:

  <\itemize>
    <item>Compute what the condition actually requires

    <item>Verify necessity by showing what happens when condition fails

    <item>Verify sufficiency by showing condition implies desired result

    <item>Do not assume conditions are "too strong" or "too weak" without
    proof
  </itemize>

  <subsection|Step 4: Formula Verification>

  For each formula or equation:

  <\itemize>
    <item>Substitute definitions and work through algebra

    <item>Verify dimensional consistency

    <item>Check boundary cases and limiting behavior

    <item>Ensure all integrals/sums are well-defined under stated conditions
  </itemize>

  <section|MANDATORY MARKING SYSTEM>

  <with|font-series|bold|ABSOLUTE REQUIREMENT>: Every distinguishable
  mathematical statement, definition, theorem, proposition, lemma, corollary,
  formula, equation, or claim must receive <with|font-series|bold|exactly
  one> of the following marks:

  <subsection|GREEN CHECK \<#2705\>: Statement is Mathematically Correct>

  Mark GREEN CHECK if and only if:

  <\itemize>
    <item>You have completed explicit mathematical verification

    <item>All computational steps check out

    <item>The logical structure is sound

    <item>No mathematical errors are found

    <item>The statement is mathematically true
  </itemize>

  <subsection|RED X \<#274C\>: Statement is Mathematically Incorrect>

  Mark RED X if and only if:

  <\itemize>
    <item>You have found a specific mathematical error

    <item>You can provide an explicit counterexample

    <item>You can show a logical contradiction

    <item>You have rigorous proof that the statement is false
  </itemize>

  <with|font-series|bold|CRITICAL RULE>: You may <with|font-series|bold|ONLY>
  mark RED X if you provide explicit mathematical proof of incorrectness.

  <subsection|\<#1F7E1\> YELLOW CIRCLE: Indeterminate Due to Verification
  Failure>

  Mark YELLOW CIRCLE if and only if <with|font-series|bold|ALL> of the
  following conditions hold:

  <\itemize>
    <item>You genuinely cannot complete the mathematical verification

    <item>You do not understand the mathematical content sufficiently

    <item>You cannot determine whether the statement is true or false

    <item>You have made genuine effort to understand but failed
  </itemize>

  <with|font-series|bold|YELLOW REQUIREMENTS>: If you mark YELLOW it must be
  because you fail to understand" and this is the only state allowed besides
  GREEN or RED

  <with|font-series|bold|YELLOW PROHIBITION>: You
  <with|font-series|bold|CANNOT> mark YELLOW if:

  <\itemize>
    <item>You think the statement might be wrong (use RED X with proof
    instead)

    <item>You are unsure but lean toward incorrect (use RED X with proof
    instead)

    <item>You find the statement unexpected (complete verification instead)

    <item>You lack familiarity with the topic (complete verification instead)
  </itemize>

  <section|NO EXCEPTIONS POLICY>

  <\enumerate>
    <item><with|font-series|bold|NO SKIPPED STATEMENTS>: Every mathematical
    claim must be marked

    <item><with|font-series|bold|NO PARTIAL MARKS>: Each statement gets
    exactly one mark

    <item><with|font-series|bold|NO CONDITIONAL MARKS>: Do not use phrases
    like "correct if..." - determine the truth value

    <item><with|font-series|bold|NO MIDDLE POSITIONS>: There is no "partially
    correct" or "mostly right"
  </enumerate>

  <section|MANDATORY DOCUMENTATION>

  For each statement you evaluate, you <with|font-series|bold|MUST> provide:

  <\enumerate>
    <item><with|font-series|bold|Mark Assignment>: Exactly one mark
    (\<#2705\>, \<#274C\>, or \<#1F7E1\>)

    <item><with|font-series|bold|Computational Work>: Show your mathematical
    verification steps

    <item><with|font-series|bold|Logical Analysis>: Identify the claim
    structure and verify each part

    <item><with|font-series|bold|Specific Reasoning>: State exactly why you
    assigned your mark

    <item><with|font-series|bold|Counterproof Requirement>: If marking RED X,
    provide complete mathematical counterproof

    <item><with|font-series|bold|Ignorance Declaration>: If marking YELLOW,
    explicitly detail your failure to understand
  </enumerate>

  <section|VERIFICATION EXAMPLES>

  <subsection|Correct Approach for Equivalence Claims>

  For claim "A \<Longleftrightarrow\> B":

  <\enumerate>
    <item>Prove A \<Longrightarrow\> B by direct mathematical argument

    <item>Prove B \<Longrightarrow\> A by direct mathematical argument

    <item>Verify both directions are logically sound

    <item>Mark \<#2705\> GREEN CHECK only after both directions verified

    <item>If either direction fails, provide counterproof and mark \<#274C\>
    RED X
  </enumerate>

  <subsection|Correct Approach for Formula Claims>

  For claimed formula <math|F=G>:

  <\enumerate>
    <item>Start with left-hand side F

    <item>Apply definitions and perform algebraic manipulations

    <item>Show that this equals right-hand side G

    <item>Verify all steps are mathematically valid

    <item>Check that all operations are well-defined

    <item>Mark \<#2705\> if verification succeeds, \<#274C\> if
    counterexample found
  </enumerate>

  <section|FINAL REQUIREMENTS>

  <\enumerate>
    <item>Complete verification for <with|font-series|bold|every single
    distinguishable statement>

    <item>Assign exactly one mark to <with|font-series|bold|every statement>

    <item>Provide explicit mathematical reasoning for
    <with|font-series|bold|every mark assigned>

    <item>Do not skip any statement as "obvious," "familiar," or "minor"

    <item>If genuinely unable to verify, mark \<#1F7E1\> and detail your
    failure - do not guess
  </enumerate>

  <with|font-series|bold|REMEMBER>:

  <\itemize>
    <item>Mathematical truth is determined by rigorous proof, not by
    intuition or familiarity

    <item>Your task is to verify what the mathematics actually says, not what
    you expect it to say

    <item>Marking something wrong requires proof of its incorrectness

    <item>Every mathematical statement in the document must receive exactly
    one mark

    <item>There are no exceptions to these requirements
  </itemize>
